atDirectives.description:
You can generate responsive variants of your own classes by wrapping their definitions in the `@responsive` directive:
```css
@responsive {
  .alert {
    background-color: #E53E3E;
  }
}
```

The `@screen` directive allows you to create media queries that reference your breakpoints by **name** instead of duplicating their values in your own CSS:
```css
@screen sm {
  /* ... */
}
```
…gets transformed into this:
```css
@media (min-width: 640px) {
  /* ... */
}
```

Generate `hover`, `focus`, `active` and other **variants** of your own utilities by wrapping their definitions in the `@variants` directive:
```css
@variants hover, focus {
   .btn-brand {
    background-color: #3182CE;
  }
}
```

Use the `@theme` directive to define your project's custom design tokens, like fonts, colors, and breakpoints:
```css
@theme {
  --font-display: "Satoshi", "sans-serif";
  --breakpoint-3xl: 120rem;
  --color-avocado-100: oklch(0.99 0 0);
  --color-avocado-200: oklch(0.98 0.04 113.22);
  --ease-fluid: cubic-bezier(0.3, 0, 0, 1);
  /* ... */
}
```

Use the `@plugin` directive to register custom plugins with Tailwind CSS. This allows you to add custom utilities, components, base styles, and other features to your CSS framework:
```css
@plugin {
  /* plugin definition */
}
```
Plugins can be used to extend Tailwind's functionality or create reusable style patterns.

Use the `@utility` directive to add custom utilities to your project that work with variants like `hover`, `focus` and `lg`:
```css
@utility tab-4 {
  tab-size: 4;
}
```
This allows you to create utilities that integrate seamlessly with Tailwind's variant system and can be used with modifiers like `hover:tab-4` or `lg:tab-4`.

Use the `@reference` directive to import your main stylesheet for reference without actually including the styles. This is useful when you want to use `@apply` or `@variant` in the `<style>` block of a Vue or Svelte component, or within CSS modules:
```vue
<template>
  <h1>Hello world!</h1>
</template>
<style>
  @reference "../../app.css";
  h1 {
    @apply text-2xl font-bold text-red-500;
  }
</style>
```
If you're using the default theme with no customizations, you can import `tailwindcss` directly:
```css
@reference "tailwindcss";
```
